  "prompt": "How much should I aim in my graduation to get into IIM A/B/C assuming I get a 99+ percentile in CAT?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down the importance of graduation marks for IIM A/B/C admissions, especially when you're targeting a 99+ percentile in CAT.\n\n**The Role of Graduation Marks**\n\n*   **Component of Overall Score:** Graduation marks are a key part of the composite score used by IIMs to shortlist candidates for interviews. They're not the *only* thing, but they definitely matter. Different IIMs give different weightage to Graduation marks.\n*   **Minimum Eligibility:** Some IIMs have a minimum graduation percentage requirement for eligibility to even be considered. Check the specific requirements of each IIM on their website.\n*   **Holistic Assessment:** IIMs aim for a holistic assessment. Good graduation marks demonstrate consistent academic performance, work ethic, and aptitude for learning.\n*   **Neutralizer/Differentiator:** With a 99+ percentile, your CAT score will likely be a significant advantage. But good graduation marks can further strengthen your profile and act as a differentiator in a highly competitive pool.\n\n**The Specifics for IIM A/B/C**\n\n*   **IIM Ahmedabad:**\n    *   **Generally favours academic consistency.** A high score in both 10th, 12th and graduation is given importance.\n    *   **No hard and fast cutoff:** There's no official \"you need X% to get in.\"\n    *   **Safe Zone:** Aim for 80% or higher in graduation to be in a good position.\n    *   **Below 70%:** It becomes more challenging but not impossible, especially with a stellar CAT score and excellent performance in other areas (work experience, interview).\n*   **IIM Bangalore:**\n    *   **Similar to Ahmedabad, they appreciate academic consistency.**\n    *   **Strong emphasis on academics.** Graduation marks play a vital role in the selection process.\n    *   **Safe Zone:** Aim for 75% or higher.\n    *   **Below 70%:** A great CAT score is crucial, and you'll need to shine in the interview to compensate.\n*   **IIM Calcutta:**\n    *   **More balanced approach:** CAT score generally has a higher weightage compared to academics.\n    *   **Academic diversity:** They also value diversity in academic backgrounds.\n    *   **Safe Zone:** Aim for 70% or higher.\n    *   **Below 65%:** Still possible, but you need to be exceptional in the other components (CAT score, work experience, interview).\n\n**General Guidelines and Targets:**\n\n*   **Ideal Scenario:** Aim for 75% or higher in your graduation. This puts you in a strong position at all three IIMs.\n*   **Good Scenario:** 70-75% is generally considered good, especially at IIM Calcutta. Your CAT score needs to be excellent, and your interview performance needs to be outstanding.\n*   **Below 70%:** With a 99+ percentile, it's still possible, but you'll need to address this in your application. Be prepared to explain your lower graduation score in the interview and highlight your other strengths (work experience, extracurriculars, specific achievements).  Focus on demonstrating your learning agility and potential.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Your Stream:** Some IIMs might have different expectations based on your undergraduate stream (engineering, commerce, arts, etc.).\n*   **Work Experience:** If you have significant and relevant work experience, it can somewhat offset lower graduation marks.\n*   **Interview Performance:** Your performance in the personal interview (PI) is crucial. It's your opportunity to showcase your personality, communication skills, and ability to think critically.\n*   **Diversity:** IIMs are increasingly focused on diversity (gender, academic background, work experience). If you bring a unique perspective, it can be an advantage.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nWhile a 99+ percentile is a fantastic achievement, don't underestimate the importance of graduation marks. Aim for at least 70-75% to put yourself in a comfortable position. If your graduation marks are lower, focus on maximizing your CAT score, building a strong application, and preparing thoroughly for the interview.\n\n**Recommendation:**\n\n1.  **Check the latest admission criteria for IIM A/B/C** on their respective websites. The criteria can change from year to year.\n2.  **Focus on your CAT preparation.** A very high score is your strongest asset.\n3.  **Work on your communication skills** for the interview.\n4.  **Craft a compelling application** that highlights your strengths and addresses any weaknesses.\n\nGood luck!\n",
